cials, and research into the archives and correspondence of governmental organizations, Berda reconstructs the institutional framework of the labyrinthine permit regime, illuminating both its overarching principles and its administrative practices. In an age where terrorism, crime, and immigration are perceived as intertwined security threats, she reveals how the Israeli example informs global homeland security and border control practices, creating a living emergency for targeted populations worldwide.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aFreedom of movementzWest Bank. 0aMilitary governmentzWest Bank. 0aPalestinian ArabsxGovernment policyzIsrael. 0aPalestinian ArabsxLegal status, laws, etczWest Bank. 0aPalestinian ArabsxLegal status, laws, etc.zWest Bank. 0aWar and emergency legislationzIsrael. 4aIsraeli-Palestinian conflict. 4abureaucracy. 4acivilians. 4aemergency laws. 4ahuman rights. 4aoccupation. 4apeace accords. 4apopulation management. 4asecurity. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Israel & Palestine.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360529940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503605299423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503605299.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles